Third-party data attribution
------------------------------------------------------------------------

EGGuard downloads and processes the blacklist categories published by the
Université Toulouse Capitole (UT1), maintained by Fabrice Prigent.

    Source:  https://dsi.ut-capitole.fr/blacklists/
    License: Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International
             (CC BY-SA 4.0)
             https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

The UT1 data is NOT distributed as part of this repository. EGGuard
retrieves it at runtime. Any redistribution of the downloaded lists — or
of derivative lists produced from them — must comply with the terms of
CC BY-SA 4.0, including attribution to the Université Toulouse Capitole
and distribution of derivatives under the same license.

EGGuard's own source code (the fetching, parsing, and policy-generation
logic) is an independent work and is licensed under Apache-2.0; the
ShareAlike obligation attaches to the UT1 data and its derivatives, not to
this tooling.

EGGuard can optionally consume feeds published by abuse.ch (now part of
Spamhaus) — currently URLhaus and ThreatFox.

    Source:  https://urlhaus.abuse.ch/  https://threatfox.abuse.ch/
             (https://abuse.ch/)
    Terms:   https://abuse.ch/terms-of-use/

These feeds are NOT distributed in this repository. EGGuard retrieves them at
runtime using an Auth-Key that each operator obtains for their own abuse.ch
account; the key is personal to that account and is not shared by this project.

The abuse.ch data is not offered under an open license. Per the abuse.ch /
Spamhaus terms of use, the datasets are provided free of charge, but:

  - commercial or for-profit use may require a paid subscription;
  - the terms place conditions on copying, redistributing, and creating
    derivative works from the data and platforms.

Each operator is responsible for reviewing the abuse.ch terms of use (and the
per-platform policies linked from URLhaus and ThreatFox) and for ensuring their
use of these feeds — particularly in a commercial setting — complies with them.
EGGuard fetches the feeds with conditional requests so unchanged data is not
re-downloaded.

